        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         "We are not in the pre-50 stage of linear evolution in pets anymore."</P><P>That's the answer to your question.</P><P>I like situational pets.  I think it adds a new dimension to EQ.  You are free to your opinion, but I don't like statements like "this should do this, period." like it's some divine rule.  I'm here to point out that the devs did not intend that rule to be upheld when they introduced situational pets, and how I support their decision to do so.</P><P>I really don't want to bring up another game here but take a look at DAOC - situational pets work and add to the fun in playing a pet class.  It's just like having clerics having two different kinds of heals - mana-costly an fast heals and slower, but mana-efficient heals.  It's the same reason Complete Heal was a mistake, because it destroyed a large part of the possibility of variety in cleric healing spells.  People complain that EQ is monotonic and requires nos trategy.  Do you really want to make it more that way?</P><P>Furthermore, if VI does not tweak the monk and rogue pet to be of comparable merit to as they were before the EoT boost (and the EOT was used a lot even before it was boosted, so I see no problems with it being undesirable), they're essentially implementing a half-hearted attempt at balance.  Half-hearted because they would not complete either the idea of having diverse, situational pets NOR would they follow the idea of having straight forward, upgrading pets ala pre-50.  If they do one or the other, I'd be content.  But if they're going to compromise half-heartedly, I object.</P><P></P><P>Etadanik the Redeemed<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
